bove everything (teamwork), excellent attention, maybe also \"keeps calm in a crisis\". Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nD: strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Weaknesses: moody, loner. No data on teamwork, communication, decision speed, calmness.\n\nNow evaluate criteria: reliability, technical competence, calmness, decision speed, teamwork, communication, professional development.\n\nReliability: B (conscientious), D (responsibility), C (concern for others), A (leadership but unfriendly). B seems best.\n\nTechnical: A (spatial vision, complex connections), B (weather, computer), C (technology, attention), D (problem solving). All decent.\n\nCalmness: B (handles stress), C (keeps calm), D (responds adequately), A unknown.\n\nDecision speed: C (quick decisions), others unknown.\n\nTeamwork: C (concern for others), A (leadership but unfriendly), B unknown, D unknown.\n\nCommunication: none have strengths; C has weakness, B has weakness, A unknown, D unknown.\n\nProfessional development: C not willing to further education (negative), B no info, A not open to new ideas (negative), D no info.\n\nThus C has strong decision speed, calmness, teamwork orientation, but communication weakness and lack of development. B has reliability, stress handling, technical, but lacks teamwork/communication strengths. Which is more critical? For long-distance flights, crew communication is vital. A candidate who cannot communicate well is risky. B's communication weakness is tone, which may be mitigated. C's communication difficulty is more severe. So B may be safer.\n\nHowever B also lacks teamwork evidence. But his conscientiousness and stress handling may indicate ability to work in crew. Also his technical skills are relevant.\n\nThus I think B is best overall.\n\nWe should also consider that we have no info on A's cal